{{Infobox hieroglyphs
|NAME = <hiero>D21-M17-M17 W17:t*t N14-N33-N33-N33</hiero> 
|NAME-TRANSKRIPTION = Tjemes-ni-chentet<br/>''rj-ḫnt.t''<br/>read as: ''Tjms-n.-ḫnt.t''<br/>''The Red One of the Ship''
}}

'''Tjemes-ni-chentet''' is the designation of an [[:en:Ancient Egypt|Ancient Egypt]] [[:en:Decan|Decan]], which comprised three {{ill|Baktiu|1=Baktiu|2=de|3=Baktiu|de|Baktiu|1=Baktiu|2=de|3=Baktiu|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baktiu|qq=}} (decan stars) and belonged to the Ancient Egyptian [[:en:Constellation|Constellation]] {{ill|Ship (constellation)|de|Schiff (Sternbild)|lt=Ship|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ship (constellation)|qq=}}, depicted in many coffins on {{ill|star clock|de|Diagonalsternuhr|star clock=star clock|lt=Diagonal star clocks|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/star clock|qq=}} and, for example, in the tomb of [[:en:Senenmut|Senenmut]]. It was located approximately at the same height as the Ancient Egyptian constellation {{ill|Sheep (constellation)|de|Schaf (Sternbild)|lt=Sheep|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sheep (constellation)|qq=}}.

The most prominent "reddish" [[:en:Star|stars]] in this decan are {{ill|Antares|de|Antares (Alpha Scorpii)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Antares|qq=}} and {{ill|Epsilon Scorpii|de|Wei (Epsilon Scorpii)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Epsilon Scorpii|qq=}} in the constellation [[:en:Scorpius|Scorpius]]. The name Antares comes from [[:en:Greek language|Ancient Greek]], meaning "opposite Ares." The god Ares was known to the [[:en:Ancient Rome|Roman Empire]] as [[:en:Mars (mythology)|Mars]], and Antares has a similar color and apparent brightness to [[:en:Mars|Mars]]. This resemblance often leads to confusion, especially since both are located near the [[:en:Ecliptic|Ecliptic]]. The Egyptian name "The Red One of the Ship" refers to the deity {{ill|Set (deity)|de|Seth (Ägyptische Mythologie)|lt=Set|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Set (deity)|qq=}}, who was also titled "Lord of this Decan."

In the decan lists of the {{ill|Book of Nut#Pharaonic period|lt=Pharaonic period|de|Nutbuch#Pharaonische Zeit|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Book of Nut#Pharaonic period|qq=}}, Tjemes-ni-chentet represented the 12th decan on the body of {{ill|Nut (Egyptian mythology)|de|Nut (Ägyptische Mythologie)|1=Nut (goddess)|lt=Nut|lt=Nut|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nut (Egyptian mythology)|13=User:Immanuelle/Nut (goddess)|qq=}}. The [[:en:Heliacal rising|Heliacal rising]] was set for the {{ill|Season of the Harvest|lt=Shemu#Dating|lt=26th Shemu IV|de|26. Schemu IV|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Season of the Harvest|qq=}}, based on the arrangement ordered under [[:en:Senusret III|Senusret III]] ([[:en:Twelfth Dynasty of Egypt|Twelfth Dynasty of Egypt]]) in his seventh year of reign.

== Literature ==
* [[:en:Christian Leitz|Christian Leitz]]: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''. Peeters, Leuven 1995, ISBN 90-6831-669-9, p. 89.  
* {{ill|Alexandra von Lieven|fr|Alexandra von Lieven|de|Alexandra von Lieven|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Alexandra von Lieven|qq=}}: ''Grundriss des Laufes der Sterne – Das sogenannte Nutbuch''. The Carsten Niebuhr Institute of Ancient Eastern Studies (et al.), Copenhagen 2007, ISBN 978-87-635-0406-5, pp. 62–67 and 385.

